 game tries to shake things up by adding a twist to the story at the end, but the player most likely saw it coming a mile away[spoiler], especially people who've seen Star Wars[/spoiler].\n\nTo make matters worse, the paper-thin story ends with 'To be continued\u2026' after defeating the final boss. So if you want to see the conclusion to the story, you'll need to buy [url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/569970/Chosen_2/]Chosen 2[/url]. Lame.\n\nThe writing is okay in that we usually get to read a lot worse English in these RPG Maker games, but nevertheless the wording is sometimes strange e.g. 'Potion was found' and 'Wanna beer?'.\n\n[h1]Gameplay[/h1]\n\nThe gameplay is typical RPG Maker. You walk around towns, enter houses and stores, leave the town and explore the surroundings where random combat may be initiated at any time. You control a party, in this case a group of four, and equip them with increasingly better gear. By defeating opponents in tactical turn-based combat, the party members gain levels, increasing their stats (hit points, magic points, attack and defense) and allowing them to learn new skills and spells.\n\nThe level design is decent. You'll find yourself in towns, forests, deserts, castles and dungeons - classic stuff, really. The game world seems open at first, but you'll soon learn that you always need to complete the next part of the main quest at location A to be able to enter location B, where the next part of the main quest will take place. So the game is actually very linear.\n\nThe combat is made interesting by adding a mix of skills and spells. Skills use TP that are gained during combat. Spells use classic MP. It takes a few levels before the party gains access to interesting skills and spells, making the first part of the game very repetitive combat-wise. Also, you'll soon find out which are the most useful skills and spells, and likewise discover that most of the other skills and spells are actually completely useless.\n\nOverall, [i]The Chosen RPG[/i] is a bit too easy, so I'm sure a lot of people would have preferred to see an option to set the game to a higher difficulty mode. The good thing about the low difficulty is that [i]The Chosen RPG[/i] requires little or no level grinding, unlike a lot of other RPG Maker games.\n\nDuring combat you sometimes get status effects that persist after the combat has ended, but there's no way to check what these status effects are exactly.\n\nYour party gains levels but the game doesn't mention how much stats they gain. You do get a notice if they gain a skill or spell, though, which is the most useful information.\n\n[h1]Graphics and sound[/h1]\n\nThe graphics are classic RPG Maker graphics. But the problem with [i]The Chosen RPG[/i] is that Windowed Mode is too small, whereas Full Screen Mode has wide black bars to the left and right of the screen, and it renders the graphics way too blurry, as graphics get blown up too much to fill the screen. So an option for an in-between size would have been very welcome.\n\nOne further gripe is that your party members are tiny. During combat, they're literally five times smaller than any human opponent, even though your party does not consist of toddlers or dwarves. It just looks ridiculous.\n\n[i]The Chosen RPG[/i]'s music is fine except for the annoying 1990s dance music in the starting town. To make matters worse, a bit later on, when that town is under attack, the music changes to a groovy jazz tune. Both are completely out of place. But okay, the rest of the music is fine and combat music is even reminiscent of classic old-school JRPGs, so it's just unfortunate that the problem with the music lies in the very first area of the game.\n\n[h1]On Steam's extra features[/h1]\n\n[i]The Chosen RPG[/i] has 5 Steam Trading Cards. You'll get 3 while running the game.\n\nFive of the 8 Steam Achievements are story-related and unmissable. The remaining 3 are granted for optional goals and therefore missable.", "comment_